{
  "doc_id": "7402",
  "text": "We also found significantly higher SAA concentration in women not treated with biological DMARDs, which indicates more active disease in these cases. However, patients in our group received therapy with different biological DMARDs (one of the three TNF inhibitors or rituximab), which hinders a reliable assessment of relationship between SAA and biological treatment. In literature, there is no data on the association between SAA and rituximab. There are few reports on the effect of anti-TNF [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and anti-IL-6 [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] treatment on SAA concentration, dealing mostly with patients with amyloidosis, secondary to RA. The blockade of TNF prevents high systemic SAA concentrations that are largely driven by TNF. The effective and early DMARDs treatment works as the primary prevention of amyloidosis, as well as the secondary prevention in a subclinical phase of this complication [CITATION_8] . However, even during anti-TNF therapy, excessive, extrahepatic expression of SAA, mediated by IL-6 and GCs, could probably be maintained in rheumatoid synovial tissue [CITATION_9] . In this case, SAA may upregulate TNF itself and may be a potent upstream mediator of TNF, influencing response to existing anti-TNF therapy [CITATION_10] . High level of SAA during anti-TNF treatment might serve as a biomarker of persistent synovial inflammation, resistant to the therapy currently used.",
